00:16:14.710 --> 00:16:19.930 align:middle line:84%
in your body to actually find
other neurons to grow and find

00:16:19.930 --> 00:16:20.730 align:middle line:90%
other neurons.

00:16:20.730 --> 00:16:22.690 align:middle line:84%
The image you're seeing
on your screen right

00:16:22.690 --> 00:16:27.280 align:middle line:84%
now is a single isolated neuron
looking for another neuron

00:16:27.280 --> 00:16:28.637 align:middle line:90%
that it can hook up with.

00:16:28.637 --> 00:16:29.470 align:middle line:90%
They're very social.

00:16:29.470 --> 00:16:31.690 align:middle line:84%
They want to hook
up these neurons.

00:16:31.690 --> 00:16:33.550 align:middle line:84%
And what you're
seeing on your screen

00:16:33.550 --> 00:16:37.590 align:middle line:84%
is what happens to many neurons
when you are doing this.

00:16:37.590 --> 00:16:40.900 align:middle line:10%
It is the act of you
striving to create

00:16:40.900 --> 00:16:44.110 align:middle line:10%
that triggers the neurons
to fire the way they fire.

00:16:44.110 --> 00:16:48.370 align:middle line:10%
This has a direct impact
and a direct consequence

00:16:48.370 --> 00:16:50.290 align:middle line:10%
when it comes to
language in the words

00:16:50.290 --> 00:16:53.245 align:middle line:10%
that we use to express
ourselves in our lives.

00:16:53.245 --> 00:16:56.410 align:middle line:84%
So one of the first
scientific links

00:16:56.410 --> 00:16:58.660 align:middle line:84%
to what I'm talking
about here-- the link

00:16:58.660 --> 00:17:01.750 align:middle line:84%
between the language that
we use and our biology,

00:17:01.750 --> 00:17:03.520 align:middle line:84%
the way that our
neurons fire-- was

00:17:03.520 --> 00:17:06.040 align:middle line:84%
made early in the 20th
century by a linguist.

00:17:06.040 --> 00:17:08.349 align:middle line:90%
His name was Benjamin Lee Whorf.

00:17:08.349 --> 00:17:11.500 align:middle line:84%
And the ideas that
Benjamin Whorf

00:17:11.500 --> 00:17:13.750 align:middle line:84%
shared in the world
of linguistics,

00:17:13.750 --> 00:17:16.660 align:middle line:84%
in the world of science-- they
were radical for his time.

00:17:16.660 --> 00:17:17.890 align:middle line:90%
What he said is this.

00:17:17.890 --> 00:17:22.420 align:middle line:84%
Number one, he said that the
way that we speak actually

00:17:22.420 --> 00:17:25.683 align:middle line:84%
influences the
way that we think.

00:17:25.683 --> 00:17:27.099 align:middle line:84%
But perhaps even
more importantly,

00:17:27.099 --> 00:17:31.480 align:middle line:84%
number two, he said the way
that we speak influences

00:17:31.480 --> 00:17:34.570 align:middle line:84%
what we think, that
our thoughts, what

00:17:34.570 --> 00:17:39.160 align:middle line:84%
we are capable of thinking
are actually linked to the way

00:17:39.160 --> 00:17:42.070 align:middle line:90%
our neurons are being wired.

00:17:42.070 --> 00:17:45.694 align:middle line:10%
One of the reasons that
Whorf came to this conclusion

00:17:45.694 --> 00:17:47.110 align:middle line:10%
is because of the
work that he was

00:17:47.110 --> 00:17:49.570 align:middle line:10%
doing with an indigenous
people in North America,

00:17:49.570 --> 00:17:52.080 align:middle line:10%
northern Arizona, the Hopi.

00:17:52.080 --> 00:17:55.300 align:middle line:84%
What he found was that
the language of the Hopi--

00:17:55.300 --> 00:17:57.310 align:middle line:84%
when that language
was translated

00:17:57.310 --> 00:17:59.770 align:middle line:84%
into English, what he
found is that the Hopi

00:17:59.770 --> 00:18:02.440 align:middle line:84%
have a very, very
different way of thinking

00:18:02.440 --> 00:18:07.540 align:middle line:84%
about us, about nature, about
our relationship to the world

00:18:07.540 --> 00:18:09.740 align:middle line:90%
and specifically about time.

00:18:09.740 --> 00:18:12.320 align:middle line:90%
So here we are back at time.

00:18:12.320 --> 00:18:14.650 align:middle line:84%
Time is the program
that allows us

00:18:14.650 --> 00:18:18.130 align:middle line:84%
to live our lives as we
do within the operating

00:18:18.130 --> 00:18:20.620 align:middle line:90%
system of the divine matrix.

00:18:20.620 --> 00:18:23.860 align:middle line:84%
What Whorf found was that
in the Hopi language,

00:18:23.860 --> 00:18:27.320 align:middle line:84%
they see everything as alive,
everything is connected,

00:18:27.320 --> 00:18:32.030 align:middle line:90%
everything is present and now.

00:18:32.030 --> 00:18:34.250 align:middle line:84%
From the Hopi perspective,
there are only

00:18:34.250 --> 00:18:36.770 align:middle line:90%
two realms of possibility.

00:18:36.770 --> 00:18:41.270 align:middle line:84%
One is the realm of things that
are manifesting in the present,

00:18:41.270 --> 00:18:44.660 align:middle line:84%
and one is the realm of things
that are already manifest.

00:18:44.660 --> 00:18:47.480 align:middle line:84%
The Hopi do not think
about time the way

00:18:47.480 --> 00:18:50.090 align:middle line:90%
that we think about time.

00:18:50.090 --> 00:18:52.280 align:middle line:84%
From their perspective,
the manifest

00:18:52.280 --> 00:18:55.370 align:middle line:84%
is everything that
has already happened,

00:18:55.370 --> 00:18:57.372 align:middle line:84%
to everything that we
can sense, everything

00:18:57.372 --> 00:18:58.330 align:middle line:90%
that we can experience.

00:18:58.330 --> 00:19:02.210 align:middle line:84%
It's what's already
occurred in the world.

00:19:02.210 --> 00:19:05.270 align:middle line:84%
From this perspective,
the manifesting

00:19:05.270 --> 00:19:08.450 align:middle line:84%
is what is unfolding
in this moment

00:19:08.450 --> 00:19:10.970 align:middle line:84%
and is actually
called in the language

00:19:10.970 --> 00:19:13.070 align:middle line:90%
the spirit of the breath.

00:19:13.070 --> 00:19:16.250 align:middle line:84%
It includes whatever is
unfolding in the moment now

00:19:16.250 --> 00:19:19.200 align:middle line:84%
as well as what's
possible in the future.

00:19:19.200 --> 00:19:22.910 align:middle line:84%
Now, these may seem like
insignificant changes

00:19:22.910 --> 00:19:25.802 align:middle line:84%
that I'm talking about between
the way that the Hopi think

00:19:25.802 --> 00:19:27.260 align:middle line:84%
and the way we
think, but they have

00:19:27.260 --> 00:19:29.870 align:middle line:90%
very powerful implications.

00:19:29.870 --> 00:19:31.760 align:middle line:84%
Let me talk to you
about the concept

00:19:31.760 --> 00:19:34.550 align:middle line:90%
of time in the Hopi language.

00:19:34.550 --> 00:19:38.270 align:middle line:84%
In Hopi, there is no
time as we know it.

00:19:38.270 --> 00:19:40.150 align:middle line:90%
There is only now.

00:19:40.150 --> 00:19:43.590 align:middle line:84%
And what Whorf found when he
was exploring the language

00:19:43.590 --> 00:19:46.970 align:middle line:84%
is that there were no
nouns in the Hopi language

00:19:46.970 --> 00:19:50.810 align:middle line:84%
to specifically refer to
the past or the future.

00:19:50.810 --> 00:19:52.250 align:middle line:90%
Everything is present.

00:19:52.250 --> 00:19:54.740 align:middle line:84%
Everything is
happening right now.

00:19:54.740 --> 00:19:56.810 align:middle line:84%
So for example,
the idea of a wave.

00:19:56.810 --> 00:19:59.210 align:middle line:84%
When we look at the
wave in an ocean,

00:19:59.210 --> 00:20:01.550 align:middle line:90%
we say look at that wave.

00:20:01.550 --> 00:20:04.160 align:middle line:84%
For the Hopi, it's
impossible to see

00:20:04.160 --> 00:20:08.780 align:middle line:84%
one wave in the moment in
time and call it a wave.

00:20:08.780 --> 00:20:12.980 align:middle line:84%
Because it is happening
now, the word is waving.

00:20:12.980 --> 00:20:16.787 align:middle line:84%
When they are looking at the
wave, we say look at the wave,

00:20:16.787 --> 00:20:18.620 align:middle line:84%
but we know there are
other waves out there.

00:20:18.620 --> 00:20:22.070 align:middle line:84%
The Hopi say that
the ocean is waving.

00:20:22.070 --> 00:20:23.210 align:middle line:90%
They actually have a word.

00:20:23.210 --> 00:20:26.720 align:middle line:84%
They say walalata, meaning
the plural waving is

00:20:26.720 --> 00:20:29.090 align:middle line:90%
occurring-- the plural waving.

00:20:29.090 --> 00:20:31.310 align:middle line:84%
So in a very real
sense, their language

00:20:31.310 --> 00:20:33.729 align:middle line:84%
is more accurate
than ours, describing

00:20:33.729 --> 00:20:35.270 align:middle line:84%
what the waves are
doing, although it

00:20:35.270 --> 00:20:40.250 align:middle line:84%
feels awkward to us, because of
the way we're wired to think.

00:20:40.250 --> 00:20:45.070 align:middle line:84%
So the Hopi are using the
same words to describe what is

00:20:45.070 --> 00:20:46.600 align:middle line:90%
or what has already happened.

00:20:46.600 --> 00:20:50.590 align:middle line:84%
They're describing a quantum
possibility that has already

00:20:50.590 --> 00:20:53.380 align:middle line:84%
become manifest, while
leaving the future open

00:20:53.380 --> 00:20:56.750 align:middle line:84%
for other manifestations
and other possibilities.

